ce:section.ce:para:
The morphological characterization of medical waste-derived CDs was analyzed by high resolution transmission electron microscope (HRTEM). As shown in Fig. 1(b)–(d), the particle size of all three kinds of prepared CDs varied from 5 to 10 nm and the average particle size was 6.5 nm for F@CDs. However, the average size was around 7.5 nm for G@CDs and S@CDs (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). The existence of lattice fringes has further supported the crystalline nature of prepared particles. The hydrodynamic diameter for F@CDs, S@CDs and G@CDs was found to be 37.66 nm, 45.66 nm and 35.99 nm respectively. The value of PDI was determined to be 0.4, 0.2 and 0.5 for F@CDs, S@CDs and G@CDs (
                           Fig. S2
                        ).

The XRD profile with the presence of sharp peaks has further supported the crystalline nature of prepared CDs (Fig. 1(e)). The major peaks for F@CDs were positioned at 18.27°, 23.11°, 24.99°, 28.15°, 32.06°, 40.43° and 45.65° which relates to the 011, 303, 100, 101, 200, 110 and 220 diffraction planes respectively. The diffraction peaks for S@CDs were observed at 2θ = 19.17°, 27.55°, 28.65°, 36.29° and 54.54° corresponding to the 011, 101, 121, 102 and 161 planes respectively. In the case of G@CDs, the peaks appeared at 2θ values of 28.34°, 29.44°, 31.87°, 36.15°, 40.62° and 45.46° were associated with 101, 121, 200, 102, 110 and 220 diffraction planes respectively. The Debye Scherer equation (D = kλ/βCosθ) was used to estimate the crystalline size. The crystalline sizes were 36.06, 38.75 and 39.49 nm for F@CDs, S@CDs and G@CDs respectively (
                           Table S1
                        ).
